  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT78-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">pāṅkaṉ talaimakaṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered to HIM by the companion.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT78" corresp="#TNV17poem16">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                peruvarai micaiyatu neṭuveḷ ḷaruvi</l>
<l>                mutuvāyk kōṭiyar muḻaviṟ ṟatumpic</l>
<l>                cilampi ṉiḻitaru milaṅkumalai veṟpa</l>
<l>                nōtak kaṉṟē kāmam yāvatu</l>
<l>                naṉṟeṉa vuṇarār māṭṭuñ</l>
<l>                ceṉṟē niṟkum perumpē taittē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent3">O man from the shining mountains,</l>
          <l rend="indent">where tumbles from the mountain-side,</l>
          <l rend="indent">resounding like the drum of dancers with wise words,</l>
          <l rend="indent">the long white waterfall high on the big mountain,</l>
          <l>pain is fitting.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">takkaṉṟu</term>: why a p.a.? Do we have to understand it as situative: suitable for the folly you have just exhibited?</note> To say: desire</l>
          <l rend="indent">[is] something good on the part of the ignorant</l>
          <l>[that is] lasting great folly.</l>
          <lg type="alternate" resp="#TVG" sameAs="3-5b">
            <l>... desire</l>
            <l>[is] permanent great folly</l>
            <l>in those ignorant of what [is] good.</l>
          </lg>

            
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>
